Barley virus - Switzerland 19970306.0505
Date: 28 Aug 2001
From: Dick Hamilton <rihamilto@home.com>
Source: British Soc. Plant Pathology, New Disease Reports, Vol 3 [edited

First record of barley yellow dwarf and cereal yellow dwarf viruses in Tunisia
-----------------------------------
KM Makkouk (<k.makkouk@cgiar.org>, Virology Laboratory, Germplasm Program,
ICARDA. PO Box 5466, Aleppo, Syria); A Najar (National Institute of
Agricultural Research (INRAT), Tunis, Tunisia); SG Kumari (Virology
Laboratory, Germplasm Program, ICARDA. PO Box 5466, Aleppo, Syria).
Accepted for publication 13/06/2001
A survey for barley yellow dwarf (BYDV) and cereal yellow dwarf viruses
(CYDV) was carried out during April 2001 covering 7 major cereal-growing
regions (Beja, Bizerte, Cap-Bon, Jendouba, Le Kef, Siliana, and Zaghouan)
of Tunisia. 1650 samples (466 barley, 765 durum wheat, and 419 bread wheat)
with yellowing, stunting, or striping were collected from 12 barley, 23
durum wheat, and 13 bread wheat fields. These samples were tested at the
Virology Laboratory, ICARDA, Aleppo, Syria, for the presence of 5 viruses
by the tissue-blot immunoassay (Makkouk and Comeau, 1994), using a battery
of polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies. Specific rabbit polyclonal
antisera were used for BYDV-PAV (genus Luteovirus, family Luteoviridae),
BYDV-SGV and BYDV-RMV (family Luteoviridae); all provided by R. Lister,
Purdue University, USA (Webby and Lister, 1992; Webby et al, 1993). In
addition, 2 specific monoclonal antibodies for the detection of CYDV-RPV
(genus Polerovirus, family Luteoviridae) (ATCC PVAS-669) and BYDV-MAV
(genus Luteovirus, family Luteoviridae) (ATCC PVAS-673) were used.
Serological tests showed that [the 5 viruses were [present in all of the 7
regions surveyed. Among the viruses detected, BYDV-PAV was the commonest,
being detected in 377 cereal samples out of 1650 tested (22.8%), followed
by BYDV-SGV (17.2%), BYDV-RMV (5.5%), BYDV-MAV (1.1%), and CYDV-RPV (0.7%).
The occurrence of the 5 viruses was higher (75.3%) in barley than in wheat
(36%). Mixed infections of 2 or more viruses were found in all the regions
surveyed.
Even though BYDV-PAV [was identified earlier (Najar et al, 2000), this is
the first report on identification and relative occurrence of all barley
yellow dwarf and cereal yellow dwarf viruses in Tunisia.
References:
Makkouk KM, Comeau A. Evaluation of various methods for the detection of
barley yellow dwarf luteovirus by the tissue-blot immunoassay and its use
for BYDV detection in cereals inoculated at different growth stages.
European Journal of Plant Pathology 1994; 100: 71-80.
Najar A, Makkouk KM, Boudhir H, Kumari SG, Zarouk R, Bessai R et al. Viral
diseases of cultivated legume and cereal crops in Tunisia. Phytopathologia
Mediterranea 2000; 39: 423-32.
Webby GN, Lister RM. Purification of the NY-RMV and NY-SGV isolates of
barley yellow dwarf virus and the production and properties of their
antibodies. Plant Disease 1992; 76: 1125-32.
Webby GN, Lister RM, Burnet PA. The occurrence of barley yellow dwarf
viruses in CIMMYT bread wheat nurseries and associated cereal crops during
1988-1990. Annals Applied Biology 1993; 123: 63-74.
