ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[BYDV was first reported in 1951 in California in oats (_Avena sativa_),
barley (_Hordeum vulgare_), and wheat (_Triticum aestivum_). There are 6
cereal-infecting viruses in the Luteoviridae, 2 (BYDV-MAV and BYDV-PAV) in
the genus Luteovirus, and 1 (CYDV-RPV) in the genus Polerovirus. 3 other
viruses (BYDV-GPV, BYDV-RMV and BYDV-SGV) are unassigned species in the
family. Luteoviruses and Poleroviruses are transmitted by several aphid
vectors that exhibit specificity of transmission.
Cereal diseases caused by BYDV and CYDV are widely distributed and are
probably the most damaging viruses that infect cereals. Yield losses vary,
depending upon field conditions, cultivar, and climate, but can range up to
100 per cent crop loss, especially if plants are infected early in their
growth. Viral species are determined by vector specificity, serology,
genomic sequence, host range, and virulence. Disease management options
include use of resistant or tolerant cereal cultivars, planting as early as
possible to avoid vector populations, and use of specific insecticides.
An online abstract of Reference 2 above provides information on other
cereal viruses including barley stripe mosaic, barley yellow striate
mosaic, and wheat dwarf viruses in Tunisia.
<http://www.unifi.it/istituzioni/mpu/najar3_00.htm> - Mod.DH
